[1
Date: Wed, 18 Feb 98 09:04:37 EST
From: DAVID W. HAUSE <hause@EMAIL.AFIP.OSD.MIL>

Bernie Husbands <bernie@whidbey.net> asked [see (02) posting cited above
"There must be more to this than I understand. I was under the impression
that arsenic tolerances could be built up by repeated (and, possibly,
increased) doses of the chemical. If these were local folks
consuming contaminated well water why is it that they just didn't build up
their tolerance levels--or is there a tolerance maximum? Alternatively,
those poisoned may have been just passing through."
Thanks for the excuse for review: see pp. 1602-1605, Goodman & Gilman's
"The Pharmacological Basis of Therapeutics", 8th ed, 1990, Pergamon Press
for the long discussion. In short, a little arsenic intake (human average
is 300 mcg per day) is balanced by excretion. I don't know how much can be
balanced, but what bad water sources (and subtle poisoners) do is raise the
intake above the excretion limit, slow build-up occurs, and toxic effects
follow. "Tolerance" implies that the excretion mechanism would have to be
induced (made to increase its capacity) and I have no idea if this actually
occurs.
--
