[3
Date: Tue, 17 Feb 98 8:12:28 EST
From: Michael Bennish <michael.bennish@es.nemc.org>

Although there might be elevated concentrations of arsenic in some of the
well water samples that were tested, what is the evidence that there have
been adverse effects from this? What is the evidence that "The victims of
this contaminated water develop lesions, tumors at diverse sites, and some
develop cancer"? Are these findings characteristic or arsenic poisoning?
Given the ubiquity of drinking well water, and the presumably long interval
between exposure and the development of cancer, has there been any
epidemiologic evidence to link cancer (or "tumors at diverse sites",
whatever that might be, or unexplained "lesions") with drinking water from
suspected sites?
What is the presumed source of this arsenic? Are the wells in urban areas,
exposed to industrial waster, or in rural areas? Is this a tempest in a
water pot, or is there really evidence to support this rather alarming
posting?
--
Michael L. Bennish, M.D.
New England Medical Center
